story.title: Dead Air - Episode 8
story.storyDescription: Halfway through a seven-hour flight to Paris, a woman wakes up to find everyone on the plane is dead except for her…
story.creator: web-uploader

author.bio: Travis Pennington is a writer, literary agent, graphic artist, and leader of a crazy pack of canines. He loves ice cream because it’s cheaper than therapy, and he’s probably the most talented horror binge watcher you’ll ever find.

story.prePaywallNotification: Everyone is dying at the airport. Can Chrissy trust her brother to help her? Read DEAD AIR.
story.postPaywallNotification: Why did Father do all those terrible things to Chrissy?! Keep reading DEAD AIR.

messages.text: I’m in one of the interview rooms in customs.
It was the only place where people weren’t dying.
I had to run away from John.
I don’t know where my brother and that kid went.
There’s a table and chair and that’s it.
Okay, I just called the police.
I’ve seen hundreds of police cars racing by.
You should get out of there.
I’ll meet you in the parking lot.
There are curtains on the far wall.
And I hear something behind them.
He’s standing behind a glass wall.
And he’s with that kid and a group of people.
They’re all dressed in white and…
And everyone is wearing surgical masks…
Except for John and the little boy.
Chrissy’s phone dings with a text.
You didn’t really want to see Paris without me, did you?
Please tell me what’s going on.
You haven’t figured it out yet?
Chrissy’s phone dings with a text from Henry Greene.
You need to listen carefully while there’s still time.
I’ll be dead in a few minutes.
Except for you, John, and your daughter.
The reason you came to Paris…
To finally meet the girl you gave up for adoption so many years ago.
She’s beautiful, and she’s going to…
Within a few hours, everything will be clear.
The people who were dead, then alive, then dead again…
Nobody was dead on the plane.
We used a mixture of drugs to slow their vitals to the point where they were barely alive.
I’m sorry we had to do this to you.
But it was the only way.
We had to make sure you released the virus.
So we’ve spent the past few years learning what scares you most.
They were just old recordings I put together.
I saw news reports on the plane.
I chatted with their service center.
EVERYTHING that happened on that plane was controlled by us.
There were no service centers or real news reports.
I know how difficult this has been.
But it’s all for a greater good.
And none of this would have been possible without your brother’s help.
His parents both died when he was little, just like yours.
I brought him to the U.S., and he learned English within a month.
I kicked open the door of that room and got away from John and my father.
I’m trying to get to the airport exit, but…
It’s the same in the parking lot.
I crawled into a luggage tunnel.
I don’t think he’ll find me here.
No matter what, don’t get out of the car.
Do you know what’s going on?
And I need you to know everything as well.
In case I don’t make it, you’re the only one who will know what really happened.
He’s dead along with everyone else.
The only one still alive is John.
If the two of you have a virus, shouldn’t YOU be the ones who are dying?
But the people on the plane, you said they were dead.
They weren’t dead on the plane.
My father explained everything a few minutes ago.
There are bodies on the road.
A little girl…the same age as Sylvie.
I should have somehow controlled myself on the plane.
Even when I thought my dead mother was talking to me.
I should have known it was just old recordings Henry had put together.
I should have known John never really contacted the FBI.
And that everything was happening to scare me enough to release the virus.
Like I said, the virus is stress-activated.
I’m not easily stressed, so they had to go to extreme lengths to make sure I released it.
They’ve always been nutty when it comes to religion.
Always talking about The Seven Plagues in the Bible.
Henry…he must have brainwashed John after adopting him.
Made him believe he’s a modern-day Noah.
And this virus is like another Great Flood.
A man is covering his mouth and nose with a bloody cloth.
He’s smashing out windows in cars.
I think he just saw me.
I’m going to crawl out of here and find you.
Blood is running down my shirt.
Please…when you find us, try to get her away from here.
Maybe, somehow, it’s not too late for her.
Maybe she won’t get sick if you take her far away.
She’s not going to get sick.
How do you know for sure?
I’m sorry I wasn’t completely honest with you when we met.
I know I told you I was looking for a French friend because I planned on traveling to Paris for vacation.
But the truth is, I once had a daughter of my own…
And I gave her up for adoption, a decision I’ve always regretted.
I paid someone to find her a few months ago.
You named my daughter Sylvie Paradis, a beautiful name.
